 rhetoric which seemed to promise riddance of slaves as much as slavery. She tells how whites came to blame the impoverished condition of people of color on their innate inferiority, how racialization became an important component of New England ante-bellum nationalism, and how former slaves actively participated in this discourse by emphasizing their African identity.Placing race at the center of New England history, Melish contends that slavery was important not only as a labor system but also as an institutionalized set of relations. The collective amnesia about local slavery's existence became a significant component of New England regional identity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 20. Sep 2019) 0aAfrican AmericansxCivil rightszNew EnglandxHistoryy18th century. 0aAfrican AmericansxCivil rightszNew EnglandxHistoryy19th century. 0aAntislavery movementszNew EnglandxHistoryy18th century. 0aAntislavery movementszNew EnglandxHistoryy19th century. 0aSlavesxEmancipationzNew EnglandxHistoryy18th century. 0aSlavesxEmancipationzNew EnglandxHistoryy19th century. 4aAfrican-American Studies. 7aHISTORY / United States / State & Local / New England (CT, MA, ME, NH, RI, VT).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCOR eBook-Package 2016z978311066749340uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/9781501702938423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781501702938.jpg  a978-3-11-066749-3  COR eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG